[[sn:Sekison Gongen]]
[[ja:石尊権現]]

'''Sekison Gongen''' (石尊権現) is a deity of {{ill|Shinbutsu-shūgō|ja|神仏習合|12=draft|12=draft}} that emerged from the fusion of the {{ill|Mountain Worship|ja|山岳信仰|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|12=draft|12=draft}}-oriented beliefs of {{ill|Oyama|ja|大山 (神奈川県)|lt=Oyama|lt_ja=大山|12=draft|12=draft}}, and enshrines {{ill|Eleven-Faced Kannon|ja|十一面観音|12=draft|12=draft}} as its {{ill|Honji Buddha|ja|本地仏|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is often misunderstood because the {{ill|Honzon|ja|本尊|12=draft|12=draft}} of {{ill|Daisanji|ja|大山寺 (伊勢原市)|lt=Daisanji|lt_ja=大山寺|12=draft|12=draft}} was {{ill|Fudō Myōō|ja|不動明王|1=Acala|lt=Fudō Myōō|2=ja|3=不動明王|12=draft|12=draft}}, but the {{ill|Honzon|ja|本尊|12=draft|12=draft}} of the Kannon-ji in {{ill|Monzenmachi|ja|門前町|12=draft|12=draft}} is the {{ill|Honji Buddha|ja|本地仏|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="#1">Daisan Chishi Chōsho (Tenpō 6)</ref> Before the implementation of {{ill|Separation of Shinto and Buddhism|ja|神仏分離|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Haibutsu Kishaku|ja|廃仏毀釈|1=Haibutsu kishaku|12=draft|12=draft}}, it was enshrined at Isurugi shrines nationwide after being invited from {{ill|Sagami Province|ja|相模国|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Amefuriyama Daisanji|ja|大山寺 (伊勢原市)|lt=Amefuriyama Daisanji|lt_ja=雨降山大山寺|12=draft|12=draft}} via {{ill|Invitation|ja|勧請|lt=Enshrinement|1=Kanjō|2=ja|3=分霊|4=es|5=Bunrei|6=id|7=Kanjō|8=zh|9=分靈|10=fr|11=Kanjō|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is also known as '''Sekison Daigongen''' or '''Oyama Sekison Daigongen'''.

== Overview ==
In Sagami Oyama, based on the ancient plain-region mountain worship described in the {{ill|Engi Shikishinmeichō|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}}, there existed an institution—namely, {{ill|Afuri Shrine|ja|大山阿夫利神社|lt=Afuri Shrine|lt_ja=阿夫利神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (Afuri no Kamino Yashiro)—and it is believed that a shrine enshrining Oyama itself as “Afuri no Kami” stood at the foothills. Within Oyama, when the once forbidden inner area was developed as a training ground for ancient Buddhist ascetics and Daisanji was established, the stone seat at the summit and the double waterfall came to be regarded as important sacred sites within Daisanji. The stone seat on the summit became the principal object of veneration known as “Sekison Gongen” at the main shrine of Daisanji (the Isurugi-sha),<ref>{{Cite book|title=Daisan Chishi Chōsho (Upper Volume)|date=Tenpō 6|year=Tenpō 6}}</ref> and in addition to Sekison Gongen, deities such as the Daitengu Shrine (present-day Okusha), the Shōtengu Shrine (present-day Zensha), and Tokuichinomiya (present-day Jichininushi) were also enshrined and venerated. The honji Buddha of Sekison Gongen was the Eleven-Faced Kannon.<ref name="#1"/> In the area where the current lower shrine of Afuri Shrine is located, there once stood the Fudō-dō, which served as the main hall of Daisanji. It is believed that during the medieval period, Daisanji—as a mountain temple organized as a single-mountain institution under its betto—comprised various members, including lay followers, centered on religious practitioners of both the {{ill|Tendai School|ja|天台宗|12=draft|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Shingon School|ja|真言宗|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the Edo period, due to the shogunate’s religious policies, the inner area of the mountain was unified under the {{ill|Koyasan Shingon School|ja|高野山真言宗|12=draft|12=draft}}, yet temples of various sects continued to exist in the temple town of the Daisanji territory. The Sekison Gongen festival, which had been observed continuously from ancient through medieval times, persisted into the Edo period, and the faith in Sekison Gongen is recorded in works such as the {{ill|Daisanji Engi Emaki|ja|大山寺縁起 (相模国)|lt=Daisanji Engi Emaki|lt_ja=大山寺縁起絵巻|12=draft|12=draft}} and the Daisan Fudō Reigenki.

