its betto—comprised various members, including lay followers, centered on religious practitioners of both the [[:en:Tiantai|Tendai School]] and the [[:en:Shingon Buddhism|Shingon School]]. In the Edo period, due to the shogunate’s religious policies, the inner area of the mountain was unified under the [[:en:Kōyasan Shingon-shū|Koyasan Shingon School]], yet temples of various sects continued to exist in the temple town of the Daisanji territory. The Sekison Gongen festival, which had been observed continuously from ancient through medieval times, persisted into the Edo period, and the faith in Sekison Gongen is recorded in works such as the {{ill|Daisanji Engi Emaki|ja|大山寺縁起 (相模国)|lt=Daisanji Engi Emaki|lt_ja=大山寺縁起絵巻|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisanji Engi Emaki|qq=}} and the Daisan Fudō Reigenki.
== Oyama Pilgrimage == During the Edo period, Oyama, along with {{ill|Enoshima|ja|江ノ島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enoshima|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 江の島}}, became a semi-touristic destination in the vicinity of Edo, and the Oyama pilgrimage flourished. Throughout the Kantō region, Oyama associations ([[:en:Kō (lecture)|Oyama Kō]]) were organized, and the sword offering known as “Nasaetachi” — originating from the legend of [[:en:Minamoto no Yoritomo|Minamoto no Yoritomo]]’s prayers for victory — became popular. This scene is also depicted in [[:en:Ukiyo-e|Ukiyo-e]], which shows pilgrims from Edo carrying large wooden swords inscribed with the name of Sekison Gongen on their way to Oyama. Representative examples include works such as “Daitō Daigan Jōju Aru ga Taki Tsubo” by [[:en:Utagawa Toyokuni|Utagawa Toyokuni]] and “Oyama Sekison Daigongen” by [[:en:Utagawa Yoshitora|Utagawa Yoshitora]]. As the Oyama pilgrimage grew in popularity, lodgings for pilgrims (shukubō) were established in rows, and guiding priests ({{ill|Priest|ja|御師|lt=Guiding Priest|lt_ja=御師|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Priest|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}) became active. The scale of the pilgrimage reached such proportions that there were as many as eight major temples, eighteen lodges, and over 150 priests.<ref>Akizato Rojima, “Tokaidō Meishō Zukkai” (Kansei 9)</ref> Moreover, the Sekison Gongen faith spread throughout the Kantō region, and in various locales, names such as “Sekison-yama” and the establishment of Sekison shrines emerged, where Sekison associations were also formed and sword offerings were dedicated. The Oyama pilgrimage associations, centered in Sagami and Musashi, extended to Anba, Shimōsa, Jōsō, Hitachi, Shimotsuke, Kamitsuke, Iwaki, Kai, Shinano, Echigo, Tōtōmi, Suruga, and Izu, with a total of 15,700 associations and approximately 700,000 households as adherents.<ref>Daisan Kaidōki (Early Meiji)</ref> Pilgrims chanted phrases such as “Zange zange, Rokkon Seijō, Ōmine Hachidai Kongō Dōji, Oyama Daiseid Fudō Myōō, Namu Sekison Daigongen, Daitengu, Shōtengu, Aiken Nōju, Ichiryū Reihai, Kimyō Chōrei” among others.
== Separation of Shinto and Buddhism and Haibutsu Kishaku == Due to the [[:en:Haibutsu kishaku|Haibutsu kishaku]] implemented under the {{ill|Separation of Shinto and Buddhism Decree|ja|神仏分離令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Separation of Shinto and Buddhism Decree|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 神仏分離}} of the [[:en:Meiji Restoration|Meiji Restoration]], the Shinbutsu-shūgō faith in Sekison Gongen was abolished. In the first year of Meiji (1868), the summit Isurugi-sha and Daisanji were reorganized respectively as the summit main shrine (along with the Okusha and Zensha) and the lower shrine of Afuri Shrine. Although many temple treasures were destroyed, the Amefuri-yama Daisanji was rebuilt near the current {{ill|Oyama Cable|ja|大山ケーブル|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oyama Cable|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 大山観光電鉄大山鋼索線}}’s [[:en:Ōyama Cable Car|Daisanji Station]], thus avoiding complete temple abandonment. Furthermore, the Fudō Myōō statue, the honzon of Daisanji, was preserved from Haibutsu Kishaku and continues to be enshrined as the honzon of Daisanji. Additionally, in various locations, some Isurugi shrines survived Haibutsu Kishaku and remain as Sekison shrines.
